                <note rend="inline" type="source">825.00 Revolutions/20: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Culbertson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-09-04T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 4, 1931—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>40. Mr. Gordon Rentschler of the National City Bank of New York telephoned me
                    today. He said that all was quiet for the time being in Chile because the
                    Government had given up on every point, that the Navy had been turned over to
                    the petty officers and crews, and that the savings bank had been taken over by
                    the clerks and the officers dismissed. If this is true, the situation, in my
                    opinion, would seem to be potentially of the utmost seriousness. The Chilean
                    upper classes are earnest and intelligent, but unless they take hold promptly,
                    it would seem that real disaster might follow.</p>
                <p>Keep Department fully informed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
